}
Stored Procedure Execution
Consider the below Stored Procedure. For example:
delimiter $$
CREATE PROCEDURE FindCustomerByNameAndDateOfBirth_SP(IN customerName VARCHAR(20), IN dob 
DATE)
BEGIN
SELECT * FROM Customer WHERE name=customerName AND date_of_birth=dob;
END$$
Mapping Stored Procedures to the respective repository interface methods can be done in four ways. 
They are
• The @Procedure annotation in a repository allows mapping methods directly to Stored 
Procedures, creating a clear correspondence between method names and procedure names.
@Procedure
List<Customer> FindCustomerByNameAndDateOfBirth_SP(String name, LocalDate dateOfBirth);
23
• When method and stored procedure names differ, use the @Procedureannotation with the 
actual procedure name as a parameter as mentioned below.
@Procedure("FindCustomerByNameAndDateOfBirth_SP")
List<Customer> findCustomerByNameAndDateOfBirth_SP(String name, LocalDate dateOfBirth);
• We can map different method and stored procedure names usingprocedureName attribute in 
the @Procedureannotation.
@Procedure(procedureName="FindCustomerByNameAndDateOfBirth_SP")
List<Customer> findCustomerByNameAndDateOfBirth_SP(String name, LocalDate dateOfBirth
• We can also use value attribute to map the method to Stored Procedures.
@Procedure(value = "FindCustomerByNameAndDateOfBirth_SP")
List<Customer> findCustomerByNameAndDateOfBirth_SP(String name, LocalDate dateOfBirth);
Mapping a Stored Procedure using @Query 
@Query(value = "CALL findCustomersAfterDOB_SP(:dob);", nativeQuery = true)
List<Customer> findCustomersAfterDateOfBirth(@Param("dob") LocalDate dob);
Mapping Stored Procedure in Entity Class 
@NamedStoredProcedureQuery(name = "<ClassName>.<ProcedureName>", procedureName = 
“<STORED PROCEDURE>”,
parameters = <Parameter-List>)
@Entity
@NamedStoredProcedureQuery(name = "Customer.getTotalCustomersByEmailId"
, procedureName = "GET_TOTAL_CUSTOMER_BY_EMAIL", parameters = {
@StoredProcedureParameter(mode = ParameterMode.IN, name = "email_id", type = String.class), 
@StoredProcedureParameter(mode = ParameterMode.OUT, name = "count_out", type = 
Integer.class)}) public
class Customer {
//rest of the code
}
The above method call can be mapped with repository methods using @Procedure annotation as 
below:
@Procedure(name = "Customer.getTotalCustomersByEmailId")
24
Integer getTotalCustomersByEmailId(@Param("email_id") String emailId);
Implementing One to One Relationship
A customer can have only one address so you can model this as a one-to-one relationship between
Customer and Address entity classes with Customer as owner and Address as a target.
@Entity
public class Address {
@Id
private Long addressId; 
private String street; 
private String city;
}
@Entity public class 
Customer {
@Id
@GeneratedValue(strategy=GenerationType.IDENTITY) 
private Integer customerId; private String emailId; 
private String name; private LocalDate dateOfBirth;
@OneToOne(cascade = CascadeType.ALL) 
@JoinColumn(name = "address_id", unique = true) 
private Address address;
//getter and setter
}
Implementing Many to One Relationship
A customer can have multiple loans such as car loan, home loan etc. so you can model this as a manytoone relationship between Customer and Loan entity classes with Loan as an owner of the relationship.
@Entity public class 
Customer { @Id
25
private Integer customerId; 
@Column(name="emailid") 
private String emailId; private 
String name; private LocalDate 
dateOfBirth;
//getter and setter methods
}
@Entity
public class Loan{
@Id
@GeneratedValue(strategy=GenerationType.IDENTITY) 
private Integer loanId; private Double amount; 
private LocalDate issueDate; private String status;
@ManyToOne(cascade=CascadeType.ALL) 
@JoinColumn(name="cust_id") 
private Customer customer;
//getter and setter methods
}
Implementing One to Many Relationship
A customer can have multiple cards so you can model this as one-to-many relationship between
Customer and Card entity classes with Customer entity as owner.
@Entity
public class Card {
@Id
private Integer cardId; private 
String cardNumber; private 
LocalDate expiryDate; 
26
// getter and setter methods
}
@Entity public class 
Customer{
@Id
@GeneratedValue(strategy=GenerationType.IDENTITY) 
private Integer customerId; private String emailId; 
private String name; private LocalDate dateOfBirth;
@OneToMany(cascade=CascadeType.ALL) 
@JoinColumn(name="cust_id") 
private List<Card> cards; 
//getter and setter methods
}
Spring REST using Spring Boot 
• Project Setup: 
o Create a new Spring Boot project. 
o Add the necessary dependencies: spring-boot-starter-web, springbootstartertest, spring-boot-starter-validation. 
o Example: 
<dependency> 
<groupId>org.springframework.boot</groupId> <artifactId>spring-boot-starterweb</artifactId> 
</dependency> 
REST Controller: 
o Create a controller class annotated with @RestController. o Define methods 
for handling different HTTP requests (GET, POST, PUT, DELETE, etc.). 
27
o Use annotations like @RequestMapping, @GetMapping, 
@PostMapping, etc. to map request URLs to controller methods. 
o Example 
@RestController public class MyController { @GetMapping("/hello") public String hello() 
{ return "Hello, World!"; 
} 
} 
CRUD Operations 
Create (POST): 
• Use @PostMapping to handle POST requests. 
• Use @RequestBody to bind the request body to a Java object.
• Example: 
@PostMapping("/users") public User createUser(@RequestBody User user) { 
// ... 
} 
Read (GET): 
• Use @GetMapping to handle GET requests. 
• Use @PathVariable to extract path variables from the URL. 
• Use @RequestParam to extract query parameters. 
• Example: 
@GetMapping("/users/{id}") public User getUser(@PathVariable Long id) { 
// ... 
} 
Update (PUT): 
• Use @PutMapping to handle PUT requests. 
• Use @RequestBody to bind the request body to a Java object.
• Example: 
28
Delete (DELETE): 
• Use @DeleteMapping to handle DELETE requests.
• Use @PathVariable to extract the resource ID from the URL. 
• Example: 
@DeleteMapping("/users/{id}") public void deleteUser(@PathVariable Long id) { 
// ... 
} 
Swagger UI 
• Add Dependency: 
o Add springdoc-openapi-ui dependency to your project. 
o Example: 
<dependency> 
<groupId>org.springdoc</groupId> 
<artifactId>springdoc-openapi-starter-webmvc-ui</artifactId> 
<version>2.5.0</version> 
</dependency> 
• Enable Swagger: 
o Annotate your main application class with @OpenAPIDefinition and provide 
metadata. 
• Configure Swagger: 
o Customize the API documentation by using @Operation, @Parameter, and other 
annotations. 
@PutMapping("/users/{id}")
public User updateUser(@PathVariable Long id, @RequestBody User user) { 
// ... 
}
29
CORS 
• Enable CORS: 
• Add @CrossOrigin annotation to your controller class or specific methods.
• Configure CORS globally in WebMvcConfigurer. o Example: 
@CrossOrigin(origins = "http://example.com") 
@RestController public class 
MyController { 
// ... 
} 
Exception Handling 
• Global Exception Handler: 
o Create a @ControllerAdvice class to handle exceptions globally. o
Use @ExceptionHandler to define methods for specific exceptions. o
Example: 
@ControllerAdvice public class 
GlobalExceptionHandler { 
@ExceptionHandler(UserNotFoundException.class) 
public ResponseEntity<String> 
handleUserNotFoundException(UserNotFoundException ex) { return 
ResponseEntity.notFound().build(); 
} 
} 
• Custom Exception Classes: 
o Create custom exception classes to represent specific error conditions. 
GSON 
