Unit Testing Spring REST Controllers:
@WebMvcTest(ControllerName.class)
This is a class level annotation that helps writing test cases for Spring Controllers. This annotation can be 
fed with the controller name that should be launched for unit testing so that other controllers will not 
come into picture when this unit test is executed.
MockMvc:
MockMvc is used to test the web layer of an application. MockMvc handles the incoming HTTP request 
and hands it off to the controller without theserver being started. So, it is preferable to test the 
controllers with MockMvc. But, make sure MockMvc is autowired to the class that performs the test.
@Autowired is used to inject the MockMvc and ObjectMapper beans that are auto-configured by
@WebMvcTest
ObjectMapper: 
This is a part of the Jackson library used to serialize Java objects into JSON and deserialize JSON into Java 
objects. It's crucial for constructing and validating request and response bodies in API tests.
@MockBean:
This annotation helps in adding mock objects to the spring application context. Mock will create a 
dummy/duplicate of an existing object and will replace the same in the application context, If the object 
does not already exist in the application context then it will create one. Mocking is quite useful when the 
bean that is required by a unit test case is not ready or unstable.
38
@DisplayName: provides a more descriptive, human-readable name for the test, which improves 
test report clarity.
Performing and Asserting HTTP Requests:
The core of web layer testing with MockMvc involves a few chained method calls to build and execute a 
request and then validate the response.
mockMvc.perform(requestBuilder): This is the entry point. requestBuilder is created using static 
methods like get(), post(), put(), and delete(), which correspond to HTTP methods.
.andExpect(resultMatcher): This method asserts the results of the request. You can chain multiple 
andExpect() calls to validate different aspects of the response.
.andDo(resultHandler): This is an optional method for performing actions on the result, such as printing 
the response to the console for debugging (print()).
Common Assertions:
JUnit and Spring's MockMvcResultMatchers provide a rich set of matchers for assertions: status().isOk() 
/ status().isNotFound() / status().isCreated(): Verifies the HTTP status code.
content().contentType(MediaType.APPLICATION_JSON): Checks the response content type.
content().string("..."): Verifies that the response body is an exact string.
mockMvc.perform(MockMvcRequestBuilders.get("/infybank/customers"))
.andExpect(MockMvcResultMatchers.status().isOk())
.andExpect(MockMvcResultMatchers.content().contentType(MediaType.APPLICATION_J
SON))
.andExpect(MockMvcResultMatchers.jsonPath("$", Matchers.hasSize(2)))
.andExpect(MockMvcResultMatchers.jsonPath("$[0].customerId", Matchers.is(1)))
.andExpect(MockMvcResultMatchers.jsonPath("$[0].name", Matchers.is("John Doe")))
.andExpect(MockMvcResultMatchers.jsonPath("$[1].emailId", 
Matchers.is("jane.smith@example.com")));
}
jsonPath("$[0].customerId", is(1)): This is a powerful feature for validating JSON responses. It uses 
JSONPath expressions to select specific elements in the JSON document and then compares them to an 
expected value.
jsonPath("$", hasSize(2)): This JSONPath expression selects the root of the JSON response and checks if 
the list at the root has a size of 2.
39
// Annotation to test only the CustomerAPI controller in a Spring Boot environment
