Spring Microservices Cheat Sheet 
Spring Security 
Spring Security is an open-source framework that is used by many for securing their applications in a platformindependent way. Security is applied in a simpler way using declarative programming approach with annotationbased configuration. 
To create custom security configuration, annotate the class with @Configuration and @EnableWebSecurity 
annotations as follows: 
@Configuration 
@EnableWebSecurity 
public class SecurityConfig { 
@Bean 
PasswordEncoder passwordEncoder() { return new 
BCryptPasswordEncoder(); 
} 
//rest of the code 
} 
@EnableWebSecurity enables web security support provided by Spring Security. 
To perform authentication, bean instance of PasswordEncoder is created. 
Spring Cloud 
Spring Cloud provides tools for building microservices applications. It simplifies the development of complex 
distributed systems. 
46
Distributed Configuration 
Spring Cloud Config Server: 
• Centralizes configuration management. 
• Uses Git or other repositories to store configuration. 
• Provides REST API to access configuration. 
Pom Dependency: 
<dependency> 
<groupId>org.springframework.cloud</groupId> 
<artifactId>spring-boot-starter-cloud-config </artifactId> 
</dependency> 
Spring Cloud Consul 
Spring Cloud Consul provides a robust mechanism for centralized configuration management in microservices 
architectures. It leverages Consul's distributed key-value store to store and retrieve configuration properties. 
Key Features: 
• Centralized Configuration: Stores configurations in a central location. 
• Dynamic Updates: Updates to configurations are automatically propagated to microservices. 
• Service Discovery: Combines configuration management with service discovery. 
Basic Configuration: 
1. Dependency: 
XML 
<dependency> 
<groupId>org.springframework.cloud</groupId> 
<artifactId>spring-cloud-starter-consul-config</artifactId>
</dependency> 
2. Consul Configuration: Create a Key-Value pair in Consul with the key as the configuration property name 
(e.g., my.app.property) and the value as the desired configuration value. 
3. Spring Boot Application: create bootstrap.yml file or application.yml file, add the following properties and 
respective values based on your application
spring:
47
application:
name:
cloud:
consul:
host:
config:
enabled:
prefixes:
defaultContext:
format:
Service Discovery: 
• Leverages Consul for service registration and discovery. 
• Automatically registers services and discovers other services. 
Spring Cloud Consul provides a robust mechanism for service discovery in microservices architectures. It leverages 
Consul's distributed key-value store to register and discover services. 
Key Features: 
• Service Registration: Automatically registers microservices with Consul. 
• Service Discovery: Discovers other microservices using Consul's DNS or HTTP API. 
• Health Checks: Periodically checks the health of service instances. 
Basic Configuration: 
1. Dependency: 
<dependency> 
<groupId>org.springframework.cloud</groupId> 
<artifactId>spring-cloud-starter-consul-discovery</artifactId> 
</dependency>
2. **Consul Configuration:** Inside bootstrap.yml file
spring:
cloud:
consul:
discovery:
hostname:

3. **Spring Boot Application:** 
@Autowired 
private DiscoveryClient discoveryClient; 
48
List<ServiceInstance> instances = discoveryClient.getInstances("my-service");
String url = instances.get(0).getUri().toString();
Advanced Configuration: 
You can customize service discovery behavior using Consul's configuration options and Spring Cloud Consul's 
properties. 
Additional Considerations: 
• Consul's DNS: Use Consul's DNS interface to discover services directly. 
• Spring Cloud Load Balancer: Combine Consul with Spring Cloud Load Balancer to automatically load 
balance traffic to service instances. 
• Spring Cloud Gateway: Use Spring Cloud Gateway to route traffic to microservices based on service 
discovery information. 
By effectively utilizing Spring Cloud Consul, you can simplify service discovery in your microservices architecture, 
improve the reliability and scalability of your applications. 

Load Balancing: 
• Uses Consul's service discovery to load balance requests. 
• Distributes traffic across multiple instances of a service. 
Spring Cloud Load Balancer provides a powerful mechanism for distributing traffic across multiple instances of a 
microservice. It integrates seamlessly with service discovery mechanisms like Eureka or Consul and automatically 
selects the appropriate instance based on load balancing algorithms. Key Features: 
• Automatic Service Discovery: Integrates with service discovery mechanisms like Eureka or Consul. 
• Load Balancing Algorithms: Supports various load balancing algorithms like round-robin, random, or 
weighted. 
• Health Checks: Periodically checks the health of service instances and removes unhealthy instances from 
the load balancing pool. 
• Ribbon Client: Provides a client-side load balancing mechanism, allowing you to easily invoke services 
without worrying about underlying service instances. 
Basic Configuration: 
1. Dependency: 
XML 
<dependency> 
<groupId>org.springframework.cloud</groupId> 
49
<artifactId>spring-cloud-starter-netflix-ribbon</artifactId> 1 

</dependency> 
Load-Balanced RestTemplate: 
@LoadBalanced 
@Bean 
public RestTemplate restTemplate() { return new 
RestTemplate(); 
} 
Load-Balanced WebClient: 
@LoadBalanced 
@Bean 
public Webclient.Builder webClient() { 
return WebClient.builder(); 
} 
2. Invoking a Service: 
@Autowire
RestTemplate restTemplate;
@Autowire
WebClient.Builder webClient;
ResponseEntity<String> response = restTemplate.getForEntity("http://my-service/my-endpoint", String.class); 
ResponseEntity<String> response = webClient.build().get().uri("http://my-service/myendpoint").retrieve().bodyToMono(String.class).block(); 
Resilience4j 
Resilience4j is a lightweight, flexible, and reactive library for implementing resilience patterns like circuit breakers, 
rate limiters, retry, bulkhead, and time limiters. 

Resilience4j with Spring Cloud 
50
Resilience4j is a powerful library for building resilient applications. When integrated with Spring Cloud, it provides 
robust mechanisms to handle failures and ensure the availability of your microservices. 
Key Features: 
• Circuit Breaker: Prevents cascading failures by automatically failing requests. 
• Rate Limiter: Limits the number of requests per time unit. 
• Retry: Automatically retries failed requests. 
• Bulkhead: Isolates failures to prevent them from affecting other parts of the system. 
• Time Limiter: Limits the execution time of a function. 
YAML Configuration: YAML 
resilience4j.circuitbreaker:
instances:
projectInstance1:
failureRateThreshold: 
minimumNumberOfCalls: 
waitDurationInOpenState: 
automaticTransitionFromOpenToHalfOpenEnabled: 
permittedNumberOfCallsInHalfOpenState: 

Usage: 
@CircuitBreaker(name = "myCircuitBreaker",fallbackMethod=”methodname”) 
public 
String myMethod() { 
// ... 
} 
Configuration: 
You can configure Resilience4j using properties or programmatically. 

Circuit Breaker: 
• Prevents cascading failures by automatically failing requests. 
• Uses configurable timeouts and retry attempts. 
51
Rate Limiter: 
• Limits the number of requests per time unit. • Prevents overload and resource exhaustion. 
Retry: 
• Automatically retries failed requests. 
• Uses configurable retry intervals and maximum attempts. 
Bulkhead: 
• Isolates failures to prevent them from affecting other parts of the system. 
• Limits the number of threads or resources allocated to a specific operation. 
Pom Dependency: 
XML 
<dependency> 
<groupId>org.springframework.cloud</groupId> <artifactId>spring-cloud-startercircuitbreakerresilience4j</artifactId> </dependency> 

Spring Cloud Gateway 
API Gateway: 
• Provides a single-entry point for microservices. 
• Routes requests to appropriate services. 
• Handles security, rate limiting, and other cross-cutting concerns. 
Pom Dependency: 
XML 
<dependency> 
<groupId>org.springframework.cloud</groupId> 
<artifactId>spring-cloud-starter-gateway</artifactId> 
</dependency> 
Spring Cloud Gateway is a powerful API gateway built on Spring Framework 5. It provides a unified entry point for 
external clients, handling routing, filtering, and security concerns. 
Key Features: 
• Routing: Efficiently directs incoming requests to appropriate microservices based on URL paths, query 
parameters, or headers. 
52
• Filtering: Applies filters to incoming and outgoing requests, enabling cross-cutting concerns like 
authentication, authorization, rate limiting, and logging. 
• Resilience: Leverages Resilience4j to implement circuit breakers, rate limiters, and retries, ensuring fault 
tolerance and graceful degradation. 
• Security: Integrates with Spring Security for authentication and authorization, securing your API gateway 
and underlying microservices. 
YAML configuration:
spring:
cloud:
gateway:
discovery:
locator:
enabled: true
routes:
- id: project
uri: lb://projectms
predicates:
- Path=/projects/**
- id: MentorMS
uri: lb://mentors
predicates:
- Path= /getmentor/**
filters:
- PrefixPath=/mentorms/
By effectively utilizing Spring Cloud Gateway, you can enhance the security, reliability, and performance of your 
microservices architecture 
